It does not seem “fair to discuss this matter with regard to the old province of Alberta and leave out the proposed new constituencies which have so few people in them entitled to vote.

I propose to say a few words with regard to Athabaska. In the ﬁrst place, the sug- gestion of some hon. members on this side that Athabaska should be added to another constituency has been taken up wrongly by hon. gentlemen opposite. There has been no suggestion on this side that these people in Athabaska shou1d have no representation We have gone beyond the time when we think people should be deprived of repre- scnatio'n if that can possibly be avoided. But what hon. members on this side do say is that Athabaska should not have two con- stituencies given it for comparatively few voters and the constituencies on the south lze deprived of their rights. By being added to another constituency the people of Atha— baska would have their representation, but they would only have what is due them and not the extraordinary representation proposed by this Bill.

Now, in reference to Atha-baska. ﬁrst of all, I want to read the words uttered by the right hon. Prime Minister yesterday. In speaking of this subject he said:

I admin at once that the suggestion‘that would at once occur to any man's mind under some circumstances would be to join such districts to existing districts.
